 central to examining ways in which myths about law are formed, and how there is inevitably a constitutive power aspect to this myth making. At the same time they explore to what extent law itself creates and sustains myths. The book will be of general interest to a number of different disciplines such as legal theory, general law, criminology and sociology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal justice, Administration of. 0aJustice, Administration of. 0aLawxPublic opinion. 0aLawxSocial aspects. 0aSocial media. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage.  aLaw.  aLegal myths.  aLegal understanding.  aMedia.  aPublic perception.1 aAmatrudo, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmatrudo, Anthony, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDraper, Matthew R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJago, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLippens, Ronnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPolizzi, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRauxloh, Regina E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRauxloh, Regina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSeal, Lizzie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Matthew R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSumner, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University